Short Answer: Before plotting the data, we need to deal with the empty string in some variables.We first treated it as NA values but after reading the original package documentation, we noticed that NA does not mean missing,it means that certain things such as kitchen,basement,etc are not appearing in some properties. So we think NA also has the ordinal information and we treated it as lower than the Po(poor condition) and placed it as the last one. Then, we decided to remove all the empty strings in the variables because they represent missing entries. From the graph, we can tell that Bsmt.Cond,Exter.Cond,Garage.Qual,Garage.Cond,Fireplace.Qu, Kitchen.Qual are approximately left skewed and the remaining two are bimodal. ### 2. Pet names

[12 points]

Data: seattlepets in the openintro package

dog <- filter(seattlepets,species=="Dog")
cat <- filter(seattlepets,species=="Cat")
dogcat <- filter(seattlepets, species %in% c("Dog","Cat"))
dogcat <- dogcat %>%
  count(animal_name,species,name='total') %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols=animal_name,names_from = species,values_from = total) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(total=sum(Cat,Dog,na.rm = TRUE),proportion=Dog/total,ratio=Dog/Cat) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(total))
dogcat

Short Answer: Before starting the question, we created a dataframe containing the animal_name and the count of each name for dog and cat, the total number of names, the proportion and ratio. The proportion is calculated by the dog/total and the ratio is calculated by the dog/cat.Also, we used na.rm function to deal with NA values in calculation. a) Create separate Cleveland dot plots for the 30 most popular dog names and 30 most popular cat names.

dc <- filter(dogcat,is.na(animal_name)==FALSE)
g1 <- dc %>%
  arrange(desc(Dog)) %>%
  slice_head(n=30) %>%
  ggplot(aes(Dog,fct_reorder(animal_name,Dog))) +geom_point()+
  ggtitle("30 most popular dog names")+
  labs(y="dog name",x="count")+
  theme_linedraw() 
g2 <- dc %>%
  arrange(desc(Cat)) %>%
  slice_head(n=30) %>%
  ggplot(aes(Cat,fct_reorder(animal_name,Cat))) +geom_point()+
  ggtitle("30 most popular cat names")+
  labs(y="cat name",x="count")+
  theme_linedraw()
grid.arrange(g1, g2, nrow = 1)

Short Answer: Before plotting the 30 most popular names for dog and cat, we first removed the NA in the animal name because it has no meaning and it doesnt make sense at all to talk about NA as animal name, so we removed it from the dataframe. Then we sort the dataframe by the count of dog and cat and then plot the graph. b) Use a Cleveland dot plot to display the 30 names that are the most dog measured by the proportion of all animals with that name that are dogs. (You can remove goat and pig names from the dataset.) Clearly state any decisions you make about what to include and not include and explain your reasoning.

dc %>%
  filter(proportion!=1) %>%
  arrange(desc(proportion)) %>%
  slice_head(n=30) %>%
  ggplot(aes(proportion,fct_reorder(animal_name,proportion))) +geom_point()+
  theme_linedraw() +
  ggtitle("names that are most dogs by proportion")+
  labs(y="name",x="proportion")

Short Answer: To determine the 30 names that are most dog names, we will be using the proportion which is already added to the dogcat dataframe at the beginning to help determine that. Then, I removed all the animal names that have proportions equal to 1 because the question says to find names that are the most dog measured by the proportion of all animals (cat+dog), those names are not shared by both dog and cat.In other word, I only include the names that are shared by both dog and cat. Then I sorted the dataframe by the proportion in decreasing order and then plot the 30 most popular names with the corresponding proportion.

  1. Find the 30 most popular names for dogs and cats combined, and create a multidot Cleveland dot plot showing the counts for dogs, cats, and total for each of these 30 names. (One color for dogs, one color for cats, one color for total.) Order the dots by the total count.
dc %>%

Short Answer: From the graph, we can tell that names with the highest total count are for both cat and dog.

  1. Create a scatterplot of popular cat names vs.popular dog names. Clearly some names are more dog names and some are more cat names. Decide on a metric for defining what is a dog name, a cat name, and a neutral name and state it explicity. What is your metric?
dc %>%
  ggplot(aes(Dog,Cat))+geom_point(col='blue')+
  ggtitle("popular cat names vs. popular dog names")

quantile(dc$ratio,na.rm = TRUE)
##          0%         25%         50%         75%        100% 
##  0.02857143  1.00000000  1.45454545  3.00000000 31.00000000
df <- dc %>%
  mutate(species=ifelse(is.na(Cat)==TRUE,"Cat","Dog"))
df$species[df$ratio>=1&df$ratio<=3] <-"neutral"
df$species[df$ratio>3] <-"Dog"
df$species[df$ratio<1] <-"Cat"
df

Short Answer: In the dataframe, if animal_name has NA in Cat column, then we treat it as a dog name because that means no cat has this name.Similarly, if the animal_name has NA in Dog column, then we treat it as a cat name. Then for the rest of names, we apply the quantile on the ratio (dog/cat). If the ratio is between 25% to 75%(1<ratio<3), then treat it as neutral. If the ratio is above 75% (>3), the we treat it as dog and if the ratio is below 25%(<1) then treat it as cat. e) Create a new variable for type of name (dog, cat or neutral) and redraw the scatterplot coloring the points by this variable. Label individual points as you see fit (dont label all of them.)

  1. What are your most interesting discoveries from this dataset?
  1. There are more dogs than cats and thus more dog names than cat names. 2.Before applied the metric, the top 5 names are for both dog and cat. But after applied the metric, the top 5 names are actually dog and neutral. 3.Most names are within the 30 cat count and 50 dog count (the rectangle at the left bottom with x-axis 50 and y-axis 30), and the most popular names are more like outliers.
  2. Applying the metric, the highest count for cat is around 50 (kitty), but the highest count for dog and neutral is more than 200.
  3. The names with labels are the most popular names for dog, cat and neutral.
  4. Another interesting discovery from the original dataframe(the one without removing the NA in name) is that there are 482 pets doesnt have names, and among those animals, there are more cats dont have names than dogs,so we conclude that people are more likely to name their dogs than cats.
  5. From the graph on part(e), we can tell that the count of dog names appears to increase as the commonness of name increases. ### 3. House sizes and prices

The largest count of houses have area between 750 and 1250 sqft and price is from \(100k\) to \(175k\). 4. The relationship of area vs price is close to the linear relationship.As the area increases, the price increases. 5. [7 points]

Data: ames in the openintro package

  1. Recreate the scatterplot from part 3 (price vs.area) this time faceting on Neighborhood (use facet_wrap(). Add best fitting lines and sort the facets by the slope of the best fitting line from low to high. (Use lm() to get the slopes.)
ames_new <- ames
neigh_sort <- ames_new %>%
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>%
  summarise(slope=lm(price~area)$coefficients[[2]]) %>%
  arrange(slope)
neigh_sort

ggplot(ames_new,aes(area,price))+
  geom_point(color='blue',alpha=.5,size=.8)+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",col = "red")+
  facet_wrap(~Neighborhood,ncol = 4)+
  labs(x='area (sqft)',y='price',title='price vs area')

  1. Is the slope higher in neighborhoods with higher mean housing prices? Present graphical evidence and interpret in the context of this data.
ames1 <- ames
ames1 <- ames1 %>%
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>%
  summarise(slope=lm(price~area)$coefficients[[2]],mean_price=mean(price)) %>%
  arrange(slope)

Short Answer: The steeper the slope the higher the mean housing prices. The mean price of most houses fall between 100k and 250k and the slope is between 50 and 150. From the graph, we can tell that its likely a upward trend but with some variations. So the higher the mean housing price, the higher the slope is.

  1. Repeat parts a) with the following adjustment: order the faceted plots by \(R^2\) from the linear regression of price on area by Neighborhood. Is the \(R^2\) higher in neighborhoods with higher mean housing prices? Are the results the same for slope and \(R^2\)? Explain using examples from the graphs.
ames2 <- ames
rs <- ames2 %>%
  group_by(Neighborhood) %>%
  summarise(r_squared=summary(lm(price~area))[['r.squared']],mean_price=mean(price)) %>%
  arrange(r_squared)
arrange(rs,mean_price)
